commentary_data: Squad: Prithvi Shaw, David Warner(c), Mitchell Marsh, Sarfaraz Khan(w), Rilee Rossouw, Rovman Powell, Axar Patel,Kuldeep Yadav, Chetan Sakariya, Khaleel Ahmed, Mukesh Kumar, Aman Hakim Khan, Manish Pandey, Anrich Nortje, Lungi Ngidi, Praveen Dubey, Lalit Yadav, Abishek Porel, Philip Salt, Ishant Sharma, Kamlesh Nagarkoti, Ripal Patel, Yash Dhull, Vicky Ostwal

Squad: Wriddhiman Saha(w), Shubman Gill, Sai Sudharsan, Hardik Pandya(c), Vijay Shankar, Rahul Tewatia, Rashid Khan, Mohammed Shami, Joshua Little, Yash Dayal, Alzarri Joseph, Jayant Yadav, Mohit Sharma, Srikar Bharat, Abhinav Manohar, Pradeep Sangwan, Matthew Wade, Odean Smith, David Miller, Ravisrinivasan Sai Kishore, Shivam Mavi, Darshan Nalkande, Urvil Patel

Hello everyone and welcome to our live coverage of Match 7 with Delhi Capitals taking on Gujarat Titans. Capitals had a forgettable start to their campaign against the Super Giants, and would look to take fresh guard as they return home after a long wait. The arrivals of Anrich Nortje and Lungi Ngidi would also be met with open arms after a toothless display with the ball in the opening game. But it's probably the batting that will need to gather themselves quickly having been ripped apart by the pace of Mark Wood at the last time of asking. The challenge doesn't get any easier today against a side that's known for its strong bowling attack that can excel in all types of conditions.

"Dimensions - 64 metres either side, 70 metres down the ground. This wicket is smack bang in the middle. Remember what we saw a couple of weeks ago in the Test match, there was not a blade of grass to be seen. This wicket has a nice even covering of grass. This is an unbelievably flat wicket. I expect there will be a little bit more pace and a little bit more carry to assist the swing and the seam bowlers. But there are a couple of parts on this wicket that are very dry. Even though they are dry, don't expect that to have a huge influence on this game. 165 is the average score here. The trend of this tournament has been teams wanting to chase. Personally, I wouldn't be against trying to bat first, get a big total and try and put as much pressure on the opposition as you can."

ICYMI, Kane Williamson suffered a knee injury while fielding in Titans' previous game, and is ruled out of the tournament. David Miller wasn't available for that game. But he has arrived now and it should be a straight swap for Titans with Miller replacing Williamson.
Aaron Finch calls it an "unbelievably flat wicket" for today's game. And the boundaries here are quite tiny as welll. Watch out for that six counter going berserk.
Some news from the DC huddle - . The 20-year-old wicketkeeper was signed as Rishabh Pant's replacement earlier this week.

Going to bowl first. Not sure how the wicket is going to play. Obviously losing Kane - we're gutted. Especially for him. As a team we can manage, but gutted for him. Miller comes in for Kane. Sai Sudharsan comes in for Vijay. Not much talking in our team. Just about keeping things simple and focusing on controllables. Pitch looks fantastic. Dew might kick in later.

Looks like a nice wicket. Have to come out with positive intent and post a good total. It's awesome. What a good turnout it is tonight. Hopefully we can make it our fortress. . It's a long tournament, going to be a few harsh calls.
(Playing XI): Wriddhiman Saha(w), Shubman Gill, Sai Sudharsan, Hardik Pandya(c), David Miller, Rahul Tewatia, Rashid Khan, Mohammed Shami, Joshua Little, Yash Dayal, Alzarri Joseph
(Playing XI): Prithvi Shaw, David Warner(c), Mitchell Marsh, Rilee Rossouw, Sarfaraz Khan, Axar Patel, Abishek Porel(w), Kuldeep Yadav, Aman Hakim Khan, Anrich Nortje, Mukesh Kumar
Lalit Yadav, Rovman Powell, Chetan Sakariya, Manish Pandey, Khaleel Ahmed
Sai Kishore, Vijay Shankar, Jayant Yadav, Abhinav Manohar, Srikar Bharat

Players are in the middle. Will be Shami to Warner first up! Both these DC openers have a good record against Shami in IPL. Let's see how it goes today. Shami to start from over the wicket, one slip in place
Shami to Warner, , good length delivery quite wide outside off, swings away late and Saha has to make a big stretch to his left in order to gather it

Shami to Warner, no run, what a peach and it looks like it has nicked the off stump on its way to the keeper!  Whew! Fuller than a length around middle, Warner is drawn forward in defence but it nips away sharply and he's completely squared up. There's a big noise as it passes to the keeper, and it looks like it's off the stump
Shami to Warner, , back of a length down leg, Warner doesn't get anything on it

Shami to Warner, no run, now an appeal for caught-behind as ! Back of a length around off, Warner hangs back in defence but it nips in and goes right through him. Good take from Saha diving to his right. There's no edge though!
Shami to Warner, no run, good length delivery slanted away outside off, left alone
Shami to Warner, no run, Shami goes round the wicket now, and only just keeps it inside the wide marker outside off. Left alone by Warner

Shami to Warner, , given as runs by the umpire, but this went off Warner's thigh pad! Length ball straying down leg, Warner tries clipping it away but misses. Runs away fine off the thigh pad! Poor delivery with Shami unable to control the movement
Shami to Warner, , goes back to over the wicket but again bowls it well down the leg-side! Nothing that Saha can do about it!
Shami to Warner, no run, back of a length on middle, Warner hangs back and tucks it to midwicket
UltraEdge confirms that the ball actually hit the off stump on 0.1! Big break for Warner! But GT seamers will be encouraged by the movement Shami found
Joshua Little to Prithvi Shaw, 1 run, short and wide, Shaw slashes hard, and it goes on the bounce to third man!
Joshua Little to Warner, no run, good length delivery on middle and leg, tucks Warner up and hits the pad. Would've missed leg with the angle
Joshua Little to Warner, 2 runs, low full toss outside off, curves away from Warner who reaches out and drives to cover. A fumble gives him a bonus couple of runs!
Joshua Little to Warner, no run, back of a length just outside off, Warner looks to pull but the ball doesn't get up as high as he expects! It sneaks through to the keeper!

Joshua Little to Warner, 2 runs, back of a length outside off, Warner hangs back, opens the face and steers it through point. Only three fielders in the off-side ring from GT as they have a couple of slips in place
Joshua Little to Warner, , oh this is a gift for Warner! Short, wide, asking to be hit! And Warner slaps it through extra cover
Shami to Prithvi Shaw, , Shami struggling to control his lines! Back of a length down leg, Shaw misses and Saha dives full stretch but isn't able to gather it cleanly
Shami to Prithvi Shaw, , width on offer, Shaw slashes hard and takes four as it ! The pace is up from Shami at 140.5kph, but the control isn't there at the moment
Shami to Prithvi Shaw, no run, back of a length on middle, Shaw clips it sweetly but straight to midwicket
Shami to Prithvi Shaw, 2 runs, 137kph, full delivery speared in around middle, and Shaw is rooted to the crease looking to drive! It goes off the inside half through midwicket
Shami to Prithvi Shaw,  Caught!!

Shami to Prithvi Shaw,  Caught by Alzarri Joseph!! Shami provides the breakthrough! Short of length outside off, rushes onto Shaw as he looks to pull and hits the splice! Simple catch for Joseph at mid-on and Shami, after an erratic start, has something to smile about.
Shami to Mitchell Marsh, no run, full outside off, nips away sharply and Marsh lets it go
Shami to Mitchell Marsh, no run, good length around middle, Marsh hangs back and defends
Joshua Little to Warner, no run, back of a length delivery on off, Warner hangs back and plays across the line but it cuts back in sharply off the seam! Strikes Warner on the thigh!
Joshua Little to Warner, no run, 140.5kph, back of a length delivery just outside off, Warner looks to cut but doesn't have the room for it! Beaten again!
Joshua Little to Warner, no run, upwards of 142kph, back of a length just outside off, Warner taps it from the crease towards point

Joshua Little to Warner, no run, wow! Back of a length just outside off, Warner looks to defend from the crease but it ! He reacts by taking his bottom hand off and hoping for the best! Luckily for him it goes down off his bat shoulder towards backward point

Joshua Little to Warner, no run, wow! Back of a length just outside off, Warner looks to defend from the crease but it ! He reacts by taking his bottom hand off and hoping for the best! Luckily for him it goes down off his bat shoulder towards backward point
Joshua Little to Warner, no run, full delivery around off, Warner's feet go nowhere as he pushes to mid-off

Joshua Little to Warner, , high full toss around off, takes Warner by surprise but he still manages to swing hard across the line. It flies away off the edge over slips and into the third man boundary! There's a review from Warner who thinks it's above the waist. But ball-tracking confirms that it's not, and
Shami to Mitchell Marsh, , back of a length just outside off, Marsh hangs back and punches firmly off the back foot through point! What a lovely shot!
Shami to Mitchell Marsh,  Bowled!!

Shami to Mitchell Marsh,  Bowled!! Chopped on! It's Shami again! He's been expensive but now has two big wickets at the top! Back of a length just outside off, Marsh goes for the back foot punch again but this is a bit further away from the body than the previous one. He drags it off the inside edge onto the stumps.
Shami to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, full outside off, Sarfaraz leaves it alone
Shami to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, fuller than a length around off, Sarfaraz opens the fac and guides it to third man

Shami to Warner, no run, 137.4kph, fuller than a length on off, slanted in from round the wicket, and Warner plays a one-handed drive to mid-off. It might've stopped on him, which is why his bottom hand came off
Shami to Warner, , width on offer and Warner feasts on it! 136kph, back of a length outside off, Warner throws his hands and slaps it over point
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, back of a length on middle and leg, Sarfaraz tucks it to fine leg
Hardik Pandya to Warner, , short of length around the waist, sits up for Warner who pulls it through square leg
Hardik Pandya to Warner, no run, 135.8kph, good length around off, Warner presses forward and punches to mid-off
Hardik Pandya to Warner, 1 run, 134.2kph, back of a length across off, Warner chops it to deep backward point
"Do teams lose a review after unsuccessful call on wide/no balls?" -- Yes!
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, 133.3kph, short of length just outside off, Sarfaraz shuffles across and defends into the on-side
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, leg byes, , straying down leg, Sarfaraz misses his glance but it runs away off his thigh pad
There's been a quite a bit of help for the seamers with the new ball. But GT have sprayed it around. And yet they've got two big wickets in Shaw and Marsh
There's been a quite a bit of help for the seamers with the new ball. But GT have sprayed it around. And yet they've got two big wickets in Shaw and Marsh
Alzarri Joseph to Warner, no run, back of a length delivery across off, Warner looks to cut, doesn't have enough room and chops it to cover
Alzarri Joseph to Warner, no run, 146.5kph, back of a length on off, Warner hangs back and taps it to mid-off
Alzarri Joseph to Warner, ,  145kph, Joseph goes full this time and Warner is just waiting for that length. He clears the front leg and hammers it down the ground
Alzarri Joseph to Warner, , down the leg-side, Warner misses out
Alzarri Joseph to Warner, , short of length delivery slanted across off, there's not much room available so instead of going hard, Warner waits on it and glides it over backward point. Superbly done!
Alzarri Joseph to Warner, no run, fuller than a length on middle, upwards of 145kph, Warner defends down the pitch

Alzarri Joseph to Warner, 2 runs, straying down leg, Warner glances it fine and the ball is racing away towards the ropes! But Little does a brilliant job at fine leg! He charges across, dives and flicks it back to save two!
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, short of length just outside off, Sarfaraz rides the bounce and fends it to point
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, short of length into the body, no room for Sarfaraz to extend the arms and he has to settle for a short-arm pull to deep square leg
Hardik Pandya to Warner, 1 run, 136.9kph, back of a length delivery on leg, Warner tucks it to deep midwicket
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, 137.1kph, back of a length just outside off, Sarfaraz blocks it from the crease
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, back of a length on off, Sarfaraz tucks it gently in front of long-on
Hardik Pandya to Warner, 1 run, short of length on off, Warner pulls to deep midwicket
Alzarri Joseph to Warner, no run, 144.7kph, back of a length delivery on middle, Warner stays leg-side and steers it to point
Alzarri Joseph to Warner,  Bowled!!

Alzarri Joseph to Warner,  Bowled!! Another batter chopping on! Nothing to do with the surface, just that the room wasn't there for him. Warner tries cutting a ball from off stump, gets cramped and drags it off a thick under-edge!
A brute of a delivery and Rossouw is gone first ball! Umpires are checking for a fair catch but Tewatia looks confident! And the replay confirms that it's a clean catch!
Alzarri Joseph to Rossouw,  Caught!!

Alzarri Joseph to Rossouw,  Caught by Rahul Tewatia!!  Umpires are checking for a fair catch but Tewatia looks confident! And the replay confirms that the catch is clean! Two in two for Joseph! Dug in short, climbs onto Rossouw as he looks to fend it off and pops up off the bat shoulder. And good awareness from Tewatia too as he's standing a few yards inside the circle at backward point. The ball is dying on him and he dives forward for a shap catch.
Alzarri Joseph to Abishek Porel, 1 run,  Length ball on middle, Porel looks to defend but it pops up in the air in front of mid-on. Lands just short of the fielder!
Alzarri Joseph to Sarfaraz Khan, 2 runs, good length outside off, steered wide of third man

Alzarri Joseph to Sarfaraz Khan, no run,  Banged in short, smashes Sarfaraz on the helmet as he looks to pull and goes high in the air. Saha thinks there's bat on it. He charges forward for a catch and dives full stretch, but can't hold on. It came straight off the helmet though. The physio checks on Sarfaraz who's fine to continue. What an over!
Hardik Pandya to Abishek Porel, 1 run, back of a length outside off, steered through point
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, good length just outside off, defended to cover
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, , back of a length outside off, Sarfaraz cuts firmly and third man is quite fine. Once it beats backward point, it's four
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, full on middle, Sarfaraz hangs back and flicks it through midwicket
Hardik Pandya to Abishek Porel, 1 run, 139.7kph, short ball around the right shoulder, and it's well played by Porel who swivels across and pulls it to fine leg. Got on top of it nicely
Hardik Pandya to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, short of length into the body, Sarfaraz whips it to long leg
Alzarri Joseph to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, 147kph, back of a length on off, Sarfaraz pats it to backward point
Alzarri Joseph to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, 147.3kph, full delivery speared in on off, Sarfaraz looks to swing down the ground but gets a thick inside edge to deep square leg

Alzarri Joseph to Abishek Porel, 2 runs, brilliant fielding from Little again! 146kph, back of a length on leg, and Porel glances it nice and fine. It's racing away on this lightning fast outfield, but Little somehow gets there after charging to his left and flicks it in
Hope Delhi uses Manish Pandey, in case the 5th wicket falls soon, as the impact player against the trend of using an extra bowler next innings. They have to shield against this collapse.
Alzarri Joseph to Abishek Porel, ,  Short outside off, Porel slashes hard, it flies off a thick top-edge and Dayal's momentum takes him over

Alzarri Joseph to Abishek Porel, no run, oh dear! , this time of the debutant! Sharp lifter that gets big on Porel as he looks to pull and clatters into the helmet. The physio runs out to check on him. Joseph is on fire here on a pitch with pace and bounce
Rishabh Pant is in attendance for this game! He appears on the big screen and waves to the crowd!
Rishabh Pant is in attendance for this game! He appears on the big screen and waves to the crowd!
Alzarri Joseph to Abishek Porel, 1 run, short of length into the body, Porel pulls it to deep square leg

Yash Dayal to Abishek Porel, 1 run, ! Full around off, Porel drives firmly down the pitch and it deflects off Dayal's foot to mid-on. They decide to go through for the single against Pandya who misses

Yash Dayal to Sarfaraz Khan, 2 runs,  Sarfaraz is through the lofted shot early, and skies it off the toe-end. It's a difficult chance for Little running back from mid-on. He does well to get to it, but
Yash Dayal to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, back of a length on middle and leg, Sarfaraz tucks it through midwicket
"Can Rovman Powell come in as an impact player in place of Rilee?" -- No, an overseas player can come in as an impact player only if there three or less foreign players in the first XI.
Yash Dayal to Abishek Porel, 1 run, steered through point
Yash Dayal to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, good length across off, Sarfaraz taps it into the off-side

Rashid brought on in the 13th over!

Rashid Khan to Abishek Porel,  Bowled!!

Rashid Khan to Abishek Porel,  Bowled!! Has Porel been done for pace here? Very full on middle at 94kph, Porel looks to drive, may have been late on it and there's a bit of turn as well. It goes past the inside edge and smashes middle stump. Rashid strikes second ball!
Look at the field here.

Rashid Khan to Axar, , bit short around off, Axar rocks back and pulls it into the long-on boundary
Rashid Khan to Axar, 1 run, full around off, Axar pushes it to long-off
Rashid Khan to Axar, 1 run, full around off, Axar pushes it to long-off
Rashid Khan to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, 87kph, full on off, Sarfaraz looks to sweep and  But it doesn't carry to long leg
Alzarri Joseph to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, 141.6kph, short of length on off, Sarfaraz fends it to point
Alzarri Joseph to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, 145.3kph, back of a length just outside off, Sarfaraz looks to pull but gets an under-edge onto pad
Alzarri Joseph to Axar, no run, back of a length on leg, Axar fends it to short leg
Alzarri Joseph to Axar, no run, 138.2kph, short of length on leg, fended back down the pitch
Alzarri Joseph to Axar, no run,  He takes his eyes off it and somehow fends it in front of short leg

Alzarri Joseph to Axar, , there's no one at the cover boundary, and Joseph offers a bit of width to Axar who's good enough to capitalise. Short of length outside off, Axar gets on top of it nicely and cuts through cover. This is an ultra-attacking field Pandya has got
Rashid Khan to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, flat length ball turning away from off, Sarfaraz steers it to short third
Rashid Khan to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, pushed through flat at the stumps, Sarfaraz pulls gently through square leg
Rashid Khan to Axar, 1 run, Rashid gets excited as Axar plays back to a delivery that's fuller than a length. He manages to punch it to long-off
Rashid Khan to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, 87kph, googly floated up on middle, Sarfaraz turns it to short midwicket

He slides across to make the stop, the ball sneaks through his hands but his trailing leg gets in the way! Meanwhile, Sarfaraz collides into Rashid while running across as they were both ball-watching. No damage done though
Rashid Khan to Axar, , too full from Rashid, and Axar launches it over wide long-on! Clean swing, excellent contact! Rashid is disappointed with himself
Joshua Little to Sarfaraz Khan, no run, full delivery slanted across off, Sarfaraz swings hard but is beaten on the edge
Joshua Little to Sarfaraz Khan, 2 runs, short of length around off, Sarfaraz looks to pull and ! But he manages to clear mid-on!
Joshua Little to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, short and wide, Sarfaraz throws his bat at it and it flies off the toe-end towards third man! Goes to the fielder on the bounce
Joshua Little to Axar, 1 run, short of length into the body, Axar pulls it to fine leg
Joshua Little to Axar, 1 run, short of length into the body, Axar pulls it to fine leg
Joshua Little to Sarfaraz Khan, 1 run, 138kph, good length across off, Sarfaraz swings hard and drags it off the inside half to deep midwicket
Joshua Little to Axar, no run, 136.9kph, back of a length just outside off, Axar steers it to backward point
Rashid Khan to Sarfaraz Khan, , fetches this leg-break from well outside off and drags the slog-sweep over midwicket! Sarfaraz starts well after the timeout!
Rashid Khan to Sarfaraz Khan,  Caught!!

Rashid Khan to Sarfaraz Khan,  Caught by Joshua Little!! Gone this time! He looks to sweep again, but only manages a thick top-edge. And Little recovers nicely after a slight misjudgement at long leg to complete the catch.
Rashid Khan to Aman Hakim Khan, no run, googly outside off, doesn't look like Aman has picked it as he looks to drive through cover. It goes off a thick inside edge to midwicket

Rashid Khan to Axar, no run, back of a length on middle, Axar punches it back to Rashid
Rashid Khan to Axar, 1 run, flat length ball spinning down leg, Axar tucks it behind square
Joshua Little to Axar, 1 run, short of length on off, Axar pulls to long-on

But they eventually get the single courtesy an overthrow. There might've been a chance to run him out with a direct hit, but what it's now done is bring Axar on strike. Pandya not happy about it

Joshua Little to Axar, , full in the slot outside off, and Axar strikes it clean over long-off! That single proves costly! Not a great delivery from Little as he misses his length and Axar - the form he's in - doesn't miss out
Joshua Little to Axar, 1 run, short of length into the body, Axar pulls to fine leg
Joshua Little to Aman Hakim Khan, no run, full outside off, driven to cover
"Cricbuzz If DC substitutes Prithvi Shaw for Manish Pandey in this innings, will that mean last batsman won't walk out to bats if all 10 wicket fall?" -- Yes
Rashid Khan to Axar, 1 run, flat leg-break turning in on off, Axar looks to sweep and mistimes it through midwicket
Rashid Khan to Axar, 1 run, flat leg-break turning in on off, Axar looks to sweep and mistimes it through midwicket
Rashid Khan to Aman Hakim Khan, no run, flat length ball turning away outside off, Aman pokes at it and steers to backward point
Rashid Khan to Aman Hakim Khan, , Aman finally makes good contact after a scratchy start! Googly on leg, he gets down low and nails the slog-sweep over midwicket
Rashid Khan to Aman Hakim Khan,  Caught!!

Rashid Khan to Aman Hakim Khan,  Caught by Hardik Pandya!! Full around off, Aman looks to slog across the line but it's the leg-break from Rashid this time! It takes the leading edge and goes high in the air. Comfortably held by Pandya at extra cover!
Rashid Khan to Kuldeep Yadav, 1 run, dances down and lunges towards the ball after being nowhere near the pitch of it! Somehow knocks it down to long-off

Rashid Khan to Axar, 1 run, slightly short on leg, Axar pulls hard through square leg and is happy with one! There was an easy two on offer with the fielder making a tumbling stop. But Axar wants to keep strike
Shami to Axar, , one-handed six from Axar! Pant, who's in attendance, would be proud! Back of a length outside off, Axar reaches out, his bottom hand comes off but he pulls it over wide long-on
Shami to Axar, no run, pulls again but mistimes it to deep midwicket

Shami to Axar, 2 runs, slower length ball on middle, Axar backs away and flat-bats it down the ground. Hasn't timed it well but has struck it very straight. Work for long-on to do, giving Axar enough time to get back for two
Shami to Axar,  Caught!!
Shami to Axar,  Caught by Miller!! Doesn't get hold of this, and perishes! Full and wide at 142kph, Axar goes hard at it and slices it off the outside half. Miller takes it easily at sweeper cover.
Shami to Nortje, no run, 140.2kph, short of length delivery that zips through to the keeper as Nortje slashes and misses
Shami to Nortje, , banged in short, Nortje advances, makes room and flat-bats it over mid-off!

Capitals finish with 162 on a pitch with plenty of pace and bounce. There was seam movement on offer as well early on. And after getting into trouble with Mark Wood in their previous match, today Capitals ran into a red-hot Alzarri Joseph who dished out a serious spell of fast bowling. He was brought in after the powerplay and after a loose first over, he rattled Capitals with some short stuff. The Titans didn't start off well with the new ball. Shami was quite erratic, though he did get two wickets. However once it was clear how much help there was from the pitch, Pandya continued to attack with his pacers. Rashid was brought on as late as the 13th over and he took a couple of wickets too. It was only thanks to some lusty blows from Axar Patel lower down the order that Capitals got to over 160. Will it be enough? We'll be back shortly for the chase.

It's been raining here in Delhi, so the outfield has changed. There was grass and there was some movement as well. There is uneven bounce, some balls bounced and some kept a bit low, there was swing as well at the start. If we take early wickets, we can win this. This is a good score on this surface. The outfield is slow. There is some dew now. We need to play good cricket to win this.

Welcome back for the chase. The DC players are in a huddle as the Gujarat openers walk out to the middle. Alzarri Joseph was the pick of the bowlers in the first innings and Delhi have a similar bowler in the form of Anrich Nortje. Let's see how DC fare with the ball.  comes in for Sarfaraz Khan. And, he's been given the new ball. A slip in position. Off we go...
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, no run, 136.6kph, away-angler wide of off, Saha slashes and misses
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, no run, 137.9kph, pitched up ball, off-stump line, pushed to point
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, , off the mark with a boundary! 133.8kph, width served and Saha pounces. Short of a length ball going away with the angle, Saha stands tall and punches it neatly through point
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, , 137.8kph, overpitched and Saha gets under it before lifting it over mid-off. Got forward and hit through the line. Back-to-back fours
First slip moves to short cover
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, no run, 138.7kph, low full toss, driven straight to mid-off
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, , 134.3kph, short of a good length ball, Saha swings across the line and makes superb contact. The ball has the wings to go over deep mid-wicket for six.

Mukesh Kumar to Shubman Gill, , Shubman Gill opens his acount with a four as well! 130.7kph, a freebie first up from Mukesh Kumar. Short and wide outside off, asking to be punished and Gill obliges. The batter stays back and slaps the cut through cover point. Speeds away to the fence
Mukesh Kumar to Shubman Gill, no run, 130.9kph, back of a length delivery closer to off, Gill defends it back to Mukesh
Mukesh Kumar to Shubman Gill, no run, 131.4kph, in-slanting length ball on middle and turned to mid-wicket. Saha eyes a single, gets rightly sent back
Mukesh Kumar to Shubman Gill, , top class shot! Short of a good length delivery, Shubman Gill stands tall on the back foot and punches it through the covers. Doesn't over-hit it. Exquisite timing!
Mukesh Kumar to Shubman Gill, no run, good length delivery that nibbles away a bit, Gill pokes at it with no feet movement. Beaten on the outside edge
Mukesh Kumar to Shubman Gill, no run, good length ball angled in, tucked to mid-wicket
Bowling change...
Nortje to Saha,  Bowled!!

Another impressive performance from the defending champions! Wasn't a straightforward chase as there was enough assistance for the seam bowlers. But Saha came out all guns blazing and scored 14 off the first over. Gill struck a couple of boundaries in the following over. But both the GT openers perished to Nortje who got the ball to nip in sharply off the deck. Khaleel bowled an expensive first over but nipped out Hardik with a peach off the final ball of the powerplay. At 54/3, the game was in the balance and that's when Sai Sudharsan joined hands with Vijay Shankar (Impact Player). The duo batted sensibly, got the odd boundaries and kept the scoreboard ticking as they forged a fifty partnership. Mitch Marsh bowled well and broke the stand and DC managed to bowl a couple of tight overs. But the 16th over bowled by Mukesh extinguished any hopes of a DC win as Miller struck two sixes and a four. Sai Sudharsan batted beautifully, notched up his second IPL fifty and remained unbeaten till the end as his team crossed the line with 11 balls to spare.

Don't think I was surprised (early movement for GT seamers). It did swing a lot more than anticipated. And from the other end it kept a little low. They showed how to adapt to situations. Got another 6 games here. Have to be on point and expect that swing in the first few overs. We were in the game till the back end. Sai batted well. Miller does what he does. With the dew also, it'll be challenging if you don't get 180-190. Was because of the wicket (Axar not bowling) - and the matchups.

Didn't have time to get jetlagged. Nice to get a win tonight. We were within range - was a matter of 3 sixes or 4 fours. Just felt like that over needed to go. We started well last year. Built really good momentum. We've got mature cricketers in the middle order - Tewatia, Rashid. Chasing a total, you can panic early. But to stay calm - we've done that pretty well. It's a very relaxed environment. There's times through the games when you get heated, but that's part of the game.

It was funny at the start, we didn't know exactly what was happening but something was happening. We gave 15-20 runs extra in the powerplay. The way the bowlers pulled back was amazing. I go with my instinct, I like to back myself. I would rather back my own decision and fall down rather than thinking something else. Most often, I rather punch first rather than take the punch. We tell the boys to enjoy there. It helps you take the right decisions. Someone's putting their hand up. We have spoken about this. Taking care of each other is more important. He (Sai Sudharsan) is been batting terrifically. Credit to the support staff and to him as well. The amount of batting he's done in the last 15 days, all the result you see is all his hard work. Going forward, if I'm not wrong, in two years, he'll do something great for franchise cricket and eventually for India cricket as well.

Thanks for backing me. A little bit nervous as this is my first time here. I was thinking what has to be done right. I wasn't under pressure, I was just calculating the right things. It was a bit low and skidding through, I was thinking to take the right options. My plan was to take the game deep and taking it through. Weathering the storm early on (was more satisfying). It was quite difficult, it was seaming initially, that was the highlight for me.

Two losses in two matches for Delhi Capitals. They were rattled by Mark Wood in their previous game and found Alzarri Joseph too hot to handle today who removed Warner and Rossouw off successive deliveries. Shami and Rashid picked three wickets apiece to restrict the Capitals to the lowest first innings total of the season. In reply, Sai Sudharsan played a classy knock and stitched a couple of half-century partnerships as Gujarat Titans romped home to win two in two. On that note, it's time to bring the curtains down on this encounter. The action shifts to Guwahati tomorrow where Rajasthan Royals will locks horns against Punjab Kings. Don't forget to tune in for that. Until then, it's goodbye from ,  and .
